u003EDuring endoscopy, only the \u003Cstrong\u003Emucosa\u003C/strong\u003E (innermost layer) of the gastrointestinal tract is directly visible. The layers of the oesophageal wall from innermost to outermost are mucosa (consisting of non-keratinised stratified squamous epithelium), \u003Cstrong\u003Esubmucosa\u003C/strong\u003E (containing blood vessels, nerves, and glands), \u003Cstrong\u003Emuscularis propria\u003C/strong\u003E (with inner circular and outer longitudinal muscle layers responsible for peristalsis), and \u003Cstrong\u003Eadventitia\u003C/strong\u003E (upper two-thirds) or \u003Cstrong\u003Eserosa\u003C/strong\u003E (lower one-third). To visualise deeper layers, additional imaging techniques such as endoscopic ultrasound are required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E**The above photograph shows the normal stratified squamous non-keratinised epithelium, with tongues of columnar lining at the distal end (Barrett\u0027s oesophagus).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endoscopy only visualises the mucosal surface of the gastrointestinal tract.","The wall of the oesophagus consists of four main layers from inside to out: mucosa, submucosa, muscularis propria, and adventitia/serosa."],"references":["Lu J, Wang Q, Zhang H, Liu J, Ren J, Fan J, Gong J, Sui Y, Chen X. Analysis of endoscopic and pathological features of 6961 cases of gastric cancer. Sci Rep. 2024 Mar 26;14(1):7159. doi: 10.1038/s41598-024-58018-6. PMID: 38532198; PMCID: PMC10965891","Ahlawat R, Hoilat GJ, Ross AB. Esophagogastroduodenoscopy. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532268/","Zhang L, Gerson L, Maluf-Filho F. Systematic review and meta-analysis in GI endoscopy: Why do we need them? How can we read them? Should we trust them? Gastrointest Endosc. 2018 Jul;88(1):139-150. doi: 10.1016/j.gie.2018.03.001. Epub 2018 Mar 9. PMID: 29526656